ChatGPT said:
Great question! Let's break it down so you get both the why and how behind it.

ğŸ¤” Why do we use EntityManager with Hibernate Envers?
Hibernate Envers works on top of JPA, and for certain advanced operationsâ€”like accessing audit historyâ€”it needs direct interaction with Hibernate internals. Thatâ€™s where AuditReaderFactory comes in.

âœ… AuditReaderFactory needs EntityManager
To get audit information, we use:

java
Copy
Edit
AuditReader auditReader = AuditReaderFactory.get(entityManager);
This lets you:

Fetch all revision numbers for an entity.

Load the entity as it was at a specific revision.

Query for revision metadata (like timestamp, revision number, etc).

ğŸ›‘ Can we use Envers without EntityManager?
âŒ Not really â€” for reading audit history
Hibernate Envers writes audit data automatically when you use @Audited. So for creating, updating, deleting, you donâ€™t need EntityManager at all.

But for reading audit history, there's no built-in JPA repository support.

That means:

You must use AuditReaderFactory.get(entityManager) to read audit logs. Thereâ€™s no JPA alternative like userRepository.findAuditById().

âœ… Where EntityManager is Needed
You only need EntityManager in:

UserService#getUserRevisions

Any method where youâ€™re querying audit tables

You donâ€™t need it in:

Create/update/delete logic

Normal service methods

Controller or repository unless youâ€™re querying Envers-specific audit history

âœ… Alternative (Theoretical)
If you're absolutely against using EntityManager, youâ€™d need to:

Write native SQL queries directly on the _AUD tables (e.g., user_AUD)

Manually parse revision numbers, timestamps, etc.

But that defeats the purpose of Hibernate Enversâ€”which simplifies this for you via AuditReader.

âœ… Conclusion
Use Case	Needs EntityManager?
Save/update/delete entity	âŒ No
Automatically track audits	âŒ No (Hibernate does it)
Fetch audit logs/history	âœ… Yes (via AuditReader)
Fetch revision metadata	âœ… Yes
