ğŸ” What is Hibernate Envers?
Hibernate Envers is a module of Hibernate that automatically tracks and stores changes (create, update, delete) made to your database entities â€” like a time machine for your data. ğŸ•°ï¸

You donâ€™t need to write custom code or triggers.

ğŸ§  Why Use It?
Use Case	Benefit
Track who changed what and when	Like a change history
Recover old versions of data	"Oops! Restore user data" âœ”ï¸
Audit logs for legal or compliance needs	Good for healthcare, banking apps
Implement version rollback	Revert entity to old state
âœ… How to Use Hibernate Envers (Simple Steps)
ğŸ§± Step 1: Add Dependency
For Maven:

xml
Copy
Edit
<dependency>
    <groupId>org.hibernate.orm</groupId>
    <artifactId>hibernate-envers</artifactId>
</dependency>
ğŸ§± Step 2: Annotate Your Entity
java
Copy
Edit
import org.hibernate.envers.Audited;

@Audited
@Entity
public class User {
    // fields
}
That's it â€” Hibernate will now:

Create a separate audit table: user_AUD

Insert a new record into that table every time the User changes

ğŸ§± Step 3: Let Hibernate Handle Audits Automatically
Hibernate will:

Track changes for every @Audited entity

Record:

Revision number

Timestamp

Entity state at each revision

No need to manually handle inserts into _AUD tables!

ğŸ” How to Fetch Audit Logs
Use AuditReader from EntityManager:

java
Copy
Edit
AuditReader reader = AuditReaderFactory.get(entityManager);
User oldUser = reader.find(User.class, userId, revisionNumber);
ğŸ›‘ How to STOP Hibernate Envers (temporarily or selectively)
ğŸ›‘ Option 1: Stop auditing for a specific field
Use @NotAudited on fields you want to exclude:

java
Copy
Edit
@Audited
@Entity
public class User {
    private String name;

    @NotAudited
    private String temporaryToken;
}
ğŸ›‘ Option 2: Stop auditing for a specific entity
Just remove @Audited annotation. Thatâ€™s it. Hibernate wonâ€™t create _AUD table for that entity.

ğŸ›‘ Option 3: Stop auditing programmatically (temporarily)
Thereâ€™s no built-in â€œpauseâ€ or â€œstopâ€ method in Envers ğŸ˜… â€” but there are 2 workarounds:

âœ… Smart Workaround 1: Use @Audited(withModifiedFlag = true) and ignore no-op changes
Only track changes when data is actually changed.

âœ… Smart Workaround 2: Use Envers listener and skip auditing based on a flag
Create a ThreadLocal<Boolean> flag to control auditing:

java
Copy
Edit
public class AuditContext {
    public static final ThreadLocal<Boolean> skipAudit = ThreadLocal.withInitial(() -> false);
}
In your custom RevisionListener, skip if the flag is true:

java
Copy
Edit
public class CustomRevisionListener implements RevisionListener {
    public void newRevision(Object revisionEntity) {
        if (AuditContext.skipAudit.get()) {
            return; // skip creating revision
        }

        ((CustomRevisionEntity) revisionEntity).setModifiedBy("admin");
    }
}
Use in service method:

java
Copy
Edit
AuditContext.skipAudit.set(true);
// perform operation without auditing
AuditContext.skipAudit.set(false);
This pretends to â€œpauseâ€ auditing for a moment.

âœ… Option 4: Audit only certain operations manually (Not recommended)
You can remove @Audited completely and manage your own _AUD table â€” but this defeats the purpose of using Envers and is not recommended unless you have full control.

ğŸ§  Summary
Feature	How
Enable auditing for entity	@Audited
Disable specific fields	@NotAudited
Stop auditing temporarily	Use custom logic with ThreadLocal flag
Start again	Set AuditContext.skipAudit.set(false)
See old versions of data	AuditReader with EntityManager
Know when & what changed	_AUD table + Envers API
